---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import indexScript from '../scripts/index.ts?url';
import rabbit2 from '../../public/rabbit2.png';

const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---
<Layout title="Moonsorter" description="Pairwise ranking for AniList, powered by MoonBit and WASM." data-base-url={baseUrl}>
  <section class="grid gap-10 lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1.1fr)_minmax(0,0.9fr)] lg:items-center">
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="pill">Fast ranking tool</div>
      <h2 class="text-4xl font-display leading-[1.05] md:text-5xl">
        Rank your anime or manga list with fast pairwise comparisons.
      </h2>
      <p class="text-lg text-latte-subtext1">
        Moonsorter learns from quick A/B picks, then generates scores you can
        push back to AniList or export as JSON/CSV. Local-first, no server
        storage.
      </p>
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <button class="btn btn-anilist" type="button" data-action="connect">
          <img src={`${baseUrl}anilist-logo.svg`} alt="" class="h-5 w-5" />
          <span>Connect AniList</span>
        </button>
        <a class="btn-secondary" href="/rank">Open ranking</a>
        <a class="btn-secondary" href="/rank?import=csv">Upload CSV</a>
      </div>
      <p class="text-xs text-latte-subtext0">
        Sessions autosave locally. You can stop and resume any time.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="card space-y-4">
      <h3 class="text-lg font-display">Flow preview</h3>
      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-latte-sapphire text-sm font-bold text-white">1</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Choose a source</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">Connect AniList or drop a CSV.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-latte-sapphire text-sm font-bold text-white">2</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Filter and slice</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">Pick top/bottom ranges or year windows.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-latte-sapphire text-sm font-bold text-white">3</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Compare</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">Answer focused A/B prompts until satisfied.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
          <span class="flex h-8 w-8 items-center justify-center rounded-lg bg-latte-sapphire text-sm font-bold text-white">4</span>
          <div>
            <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Publish</p>
            <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">Review the table, export, or upload scores.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-6">
    <div class="space-y-2">
      <div class="pill">Two entry points</div>
      <h3 class="text-2xl font-display md:text-3xl">Pick the flow that fits.</h3>
      <p class="text-latte-subtext1">
        AniList sync gives you metadata and score formats. CSV import keeps you
        offline and flexible.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      <article class="card space-y-4">
        <h4 class="text-lg font-display">AniList sync</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
          Pull your list, apply year filters, then push the updated scores back
          when you are done.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-4 text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
          <li>Supports anime and manga</li>
          <li>Preserves your scoring scale</li>
          <li>Upload only selected results</li>
        </ul>
        <a class="btn" href="/rank?import=anilist">Continue to AniList import</a>
      </article>
      <article class="card space-y-4">
        <h4 class="text-lg font-display">CSV upload</h4>
        <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
          Bring your own list. Include optional scores, IDs, and year columns.
        </p>
        <ul class="list-disc space-y-2 pl-4 text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
          <li>Works without OAuth</li>
          <li>Compatible with JSON/CSV exports</li>
          <li>Ideal for custom datasets</li>
        </ul>
        <a class="btn-secondary" href="/rank?import=csv">Upload CSV</a>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-6">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="flex flex-col gap-6 md:flex-row md:items-start">
        <div class="flex justify-center md:justify-start">
          <Image
            src={rabbit2}
            alt="Rabbit lecturer"
            class="h-40 w-40 rounded-full object-contain md:h-48 md:w-48"
            loading="lazy"
          />
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4 md:pt-1">
          <div class="pill">How it works</div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-display">How does it work?</h3>
          <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
            Moonsorter uses a statistical model to learn your preferences from quick A/B comparisons.
            It figures out which items you haven't decided between yet and asks about those first,
            so you don't waste time on obvious choices. Stop whenever the ranking looks right to you.
          </p>
          <p class="text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
            If you're rescoring an existing list, your current scores act as a starting point
            so the model won't make wild changes from just a few comparisons.
          </p>
          <details class="mt-3 text-xs">
            <summary class="cursor-pointer font-semibold text-latte-subtext0 hover:text-latte-text">Technical details</summary>
            <div class="mt-2 space-y-2 text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
              <p>
                Moonsorter fits a <strong>Plackett-Luce preference model</strong> to your choices.
                A/B comparisons are two-item rankings, while group ordering supplies richer ranking events.
                For rescoring, original scores seed the model as a soft prior (<strong>MAP regularization</strong>).
                Pair selection uses active-learning policies (A-optimal or Thompson-style).
                Uncertainty via <strong>bootstrap resampling</strong>. Tier list uses <strong>1D k-means</strong>.
                Inspired by Gwern's Resorter and newer preference-learning research.
              </p>
            </div>
          </details>
          <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3 text-xs text-latte-subtext0">
            <span class="uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-latte-subtext0">Further reading</span>
            <a class="underline decoration-latte-sapphire/60 hover:text-latte-text" href="https://gwern.net/resorter">Gwern's Resorter</a>
            <a class="underline decoration-latte-sapphire/60 hover:text-latte-text" href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plackett%E2%80%93Luce_model">Plackett-Luce (Wikipedia)</a>
            <a class="underline decoration-latte-sapphire/60 hover:text-latte-text" href="https://projecteuclid.org/journals/annals-of-statistics/volume-32/issue-1/MM-algorithms-for-generalized-Bradley-Terry-models/10.1214/aos/1079120141.full">MM for Bradley-Terry (Hunter, 2004)</a>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="card space-y-4">
      <div class="pill">FAQ</div>
      <div class="space-y-3 text-sm text-latte-subtext1">
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">But why?</p>
          <p>I wanted an easier way to 're-sort' my rankings. For example, ordering my 'top things watched/listened to in a year' and the like. Additionally, things like reranking top items or wanting to rescale things. I made a terminal program for this but then I was too lazy to use it, WebUIs are less effort.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Why all this math?</p>
          <p>Designed to be simple to use but powerful if you want to dig into the settings. Most options have sensible defaults - import your list, pick which item is better, repeat until you're happy with the order, then export or upload.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">Do you store my data?</p>
          <p>Nope. This is a statically generated site with no database. Sessions live in your browser unless you export or upload.</p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="font-semibold text-latte-text">How many comparisons does it usually take?</p>
          <p>Usually far fewer than full sorting. You can stop once the table feels right.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <script type="module" src={indexScript}></script>
</Layout>
